Looking for correlation between mobility & reproduction rate¶

Overview of analysis methods: https://towardsdatascience.com/inferring-causality-in-time-series-data-b8b75fe52c46

Example of analysis of multivariable time series analysis: https://towardsdatascience.com/granger-causality-and-vector-auto-regressive-model-for-time-series-forecasting-3226a64889a6#_=_ Note that the VAR model applies to series whose mean does not vary over time - not applicable to COVID data

  1. Pearson coefficient

  2. Linear regression - model reproduction rate using linear combination of mobility data

  3. Cross correlation - measure of similarity of two series, as a function of displacement https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross-correlation Numpy has a correlation function

  4. Granger causality - hypothesis test for determining if one series is useful in forecasting another https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Granger_causality. Predictive causality, not just correlation. Statsmodels can do this

# common_countries = sorted(list(set(Goog_countries).intersection(owid_countries))) # list of countries to compare mobility & R rate

common_countries = ['Germany','Italy','Sweden','Taiwan','United States','United Kingdom']

country_spear = [0]*len(common_countries)
const = [0]*len(common_countries)
slope = [0]*len(common_countries)
rsq = [0]*len(common_countries)

for i in range(len(common_countries)):
    
    country_spear[i],_ = spearmanr(d_stringmob[common_countries[i]+'_mobility_residential'],\
                                 d_stringmob[common_countries[i]+'_stringency'], nan_policy='omit')
    
#     plt.figure(figsize=[10,3])
#     ax = plt.subplot(1,2,1)
#     ax = plt.figure(figsize=[10,3])
    d_stringmob.plot.scatter(x=common_countries[i]+'_stringency',y= common_countries[i]+'_mobility_residential', figsize=[8,5], label='actual')
#     plt.yscale('log')
#     ax = plt.subplot(1,2,2)
#     d_stringmob.plot(y=[common_countries[i]+'_mobility_residential', common_countries[i]+'_stringency'],ax=ax)

    

    # linear regression
    Y = np.log(d_stringmob[common_countries[i]+'_mobility_residential'])
    Y.replace(-np.inf, np.nan, inplace=True)
    X = d_stringmob[common_countries[i]+'_stringency']
    X = sm.add_constant(X)
    model = sm.OLS(Y,X,missing='drop')
    results = model.fit()
    const[i], slope[i] = results.params
    rsq[i] = results.rsquared
    
    print(common_countries[i], 'spear', country_spear[i], 'const', const[i], 'slope', slope[i], 'rsquared', rsq[i])
    
    X_predict = np.linspace(0,100,100)
    Y_predict = np.exp(const[i] + slope[i]*X_predict)
#     ax = plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    plt.plot(X_predict, Y_predict, label='model')
    plt.xlabel('Stringency Index')
    plt.ylabel('Time spent at home / % change from baseline')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title(common_countries[i])
    plt.yscale('log')
